Cymbopogon nardus var. lenabatu

   [5124.jpg]
    Authority
      Family    Liliopsida:Commelinidae:Cyperales:Gramineae
     Synonyms
   Common names
      Editor
   Ecocrop code 5124

   Notes
   BRIEF DESCRIPTION A robust, stoloniferous grass with relatively broad
   leaves reaching a height of 0.5-1 m. USES An oil is extracted and used
   for perfuming low-priced technical products such as detergents, sprays,
   and polishes. The Ceylon variety yields about half as much essential
   oil as the Java type and the oil is of less quality. GROWING PERIOD
   Perennial grass. First harvest at about 240 days and then continues
   every 90-120 days for 10-15 years. COMMON NAMES False citronella,
   Citronella, Nardus grass Ceylon, Naid grass. FURTHER INF False
   citronella is cultivated in southern Sri Lanka it is hardier than the
   Java variety and can be grown on poorer soils. It can be grown from sea
   level to 1500 m in elevation. It is common in grassland open woodland
   of Acacia and Combretum on the hills in Uganda.

   Sources
